context: The chapter house has an original <a0_0><b4_0>mid-13th-century<b4_0/><a0_0/> tiled pavement. A door within the vestibule dates from around <a1_0><b5_0>1050<b5_0/><a1_0/> and is believed to be the oldest in England.[citation needed] The exterior includes flying buttresses added in <a2_0><b6_0><b8_0>the 14th century<b8_0/><b6_0/><a2_0/> and a leaded tent-lantern roof on an iron frame designed by Scott. The Chapter house was originally used in the 13th century by Benedictine monks for daily meetings. It later became a meeting place of the <a3_0><b7_0>King's Great Council and the Commons<b7_0/><a3_0/>, predecessors of Parliament.
